React is intimidating.

But it doesn’t need to be. If you know where to look and what concepts to learn first, you can get up and running in less than a week.

Follow this guide to break the learning down into 3 simple steps. Start by learning the fundamentals, then poke through some example React projects, and finally create your first React app.

1

Learn the fundamentals

Spend your first couple days going through one of these beginner React courses.

Treehouse
React Basics
3 hours • Trial
Treehouse's React intro course is easy to follow and highly polished. You'll watch videos and complete code excercises in a browser sandbox environment. One drawback, the course is a bit dated and they teach you some older javascript syntax.
Start course
Codecademy
React 101
4 hours • Trial
Codecademy's React 101 course is perfect for people new to JavaScript. You'll learn the core React concepts by completing dozens of small code challenges.
Start course
Egghead
React for Beginners
2 hours • Free
These videos are fast paced and probably best for people with some JavaScript experience. That said, the content is great and Kent Dodds is an excellent teacher. If you enjoy this course, check out Egghead's other React courses.
Start course

Then, if you want a more comprehensive course, check out learnreact.design, Design+Code, or one of these resources.

If you haven't used JavaScript before, you may find some of the content in these courses complicated. That's totally fine. The JavaScript concepts you need for React aren't limitless and you'll get the hang of it before long.

2

Read other people's code

Now that you know the basics, go explore a couple open source projects to see how React looks in action. Pro tip: Install Octotree for Chrome to navigate Github projects.

NEW
Framer X component teardowns →
Calculator
A simple calculator React app
This functional calculator app is well designed and simple enough to follow along. Start with App.js in the /src/components folder and see if you can follow the flow of components.
View code
ustwo.com
A beautiful static site built on React
The creators of Monument Valley were kind enough to open source their team's website. You can spend hours clicking through each component in the /src/app/components folder. Check out the Hero and Carousel components!
View code
Tic Tac Toe
A step-by-step guide to build a game
This is the official tutorial found on the reactjs.org website. You can either follow the steps to build the game yourself or just skip to the end and view the final source code.
View code

As you explore other people's React apps, keep an eye out for common JavaScript patterns. You should start to recognize some of the concepts you've learned.

3

Make your first React component

You should feel ready to start building. Use the create-react-app boilerplate to get a basic React app up in just a couple minutes.

Install Node
Download the Node installer app
NPM is a package manager that the React community uses to share modules like the create-react-app or react-router. You'll need to install Node.js to be able to run any npm or npx install commands.
Download Node
create-react-app
Create a simple boilerplate React app
Almost every guide you read will recommend that you create a react app using this npm package built by Facebook. You can use Guppy for Mac to run this command if you're not comfortable with the terminal.
View guide
Guppy
A GUI to manage your React apps
This macOS app helps you create, run, and manage your React apps. It's ultimately just an interface for the terminal commands you would otherwise be running, so if you prefer a CLI this may not be for you.
Download Guppy

From here on, the path will be different for everyone. Go join a React community, build a Framer X prototype, or maybe redesign your portfolio.

See, not intimidating at all.
